('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:64e249d0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘sin embargo’ and ‘aunque’ are examples of negatives."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "They are CONNECTORS (however / although), not negatives."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:bf3278c8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "When do I use (or drop) subject pronouns?", "reading": "<p>Subject pronouns are <span data-say=\"yo\">yo</span> (I), <span data-say=\"tú\">tú</span> (you), <span data-say=\"él\">él</span> / <span data-say=\"ella\">ella</span> (he/she), <span data-say=\"nosotros\">nosotros / nosotras</span> (we), <span data-say=\"vosotros\">vosotros / vosotras</span> (you all) and <span data-say=\"ellos\">ellos</span> / <span data-say=\"ellas\">ellas</span> (they).</p>\n            <p>Spanish verb endings already show <em>who</em> is doing the action, so subject pronouns are usually <strong>dropped</strong>: <span data-say=\"Hablo español.\">Hablo español.</span> (I speak Spanish) needs no ‘yo’.</p>\n            <p>Keep the pronoun only for <strong>emphasis or contrast</strong>: <span data-say=\"Yo prefiero el fútbol, pero él prefiere el baloncesto.\">Yo prefiero el fútbol, pero él prefiere el baloncesto.</span> — <em>I prefer football, but he prefers basketball.</em></p>", "question": "Why does Spanish often drop ‘yo’, ‘tú’, etc.?", "options": ["the verb ending already shows who is doing the action", "subject pronouns are considered rude in spoken Spanish", "subject pronouns only exist for plural forms", "Spanish sentences never contain a conjugated verb"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The verb ending (hablo, hablas, habla…) already tells you the subject, so the pronoun is optional unless you need emphasis or contrast."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:459b64a0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Direct object pronouns: lo, la, los, las", "reading": "<p>Use a <strong>direct object pronoun</strong> to avoid repeating a noun you have just mentioned: <span data-say=\"lo\">lo</span> (him/it, masc.), <span data-say=\"la\">la</span> (her/it, fem.), <span data-say=\"los\">los</span> (them, masc.), <span data-say=\"las\">las</span> (them, fem.).</p>\n            <p>Position: put it <strong>before a conjugated verb</strong> — <span data-say=\"¿Tienes el libro?\">¿Tienes el libro?</span> <span data-say=\"Sí, lo tengo.\">Sí, lo tengo.</span> (Yes, I have it) — or <strong>attach it to an infinitive</strong>: <span data-say=\"Voy a verlo.\">Voy a verlo.</span> (I’m going to watch it).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"lo veo\">lo veo</span></td><td>I see him / it (masc.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"la veo\">la veo</span></td><td>I see her / it (fem.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"los veo\">los veo</span></td><td>I see them (masc.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"las veo\">las veo</span></td><td>I see them (fem.)</td></tr>\n            </table>", "question": "Where does the direct object pronoun ‘lo’ go with a conjugated verb like ‘veo’?", "options": ["before the verb: lo veo", "after the verb with a gap: veo lo", "attached to the end of the conjugated verb: veolo", "it can never be used with a conjugated verb"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "With a conjugated verb the pronoun goes immediately before it: lo veo. It only attaches to the END of an infinitive or gerund."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:e7578967', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Indirect object and reflexive pronouns", "reading": "<p><strong>Indirect object pronouns</strong> (to/for whom) are <span data-say=\"me\">me</span>, <span data-say=\"te\">te</span>, <span data-say=\"le\">le</span>, <span data-say=\"nos\">nos</span>: <span data-say=\"Le doy el regalo a mi madre.\">Le doy el regalo a mi madre.</span> (I give the present to my mother.)</p>\n            <p><strong>Reflexive pronouns</strong> (me, te, se, nos, os, se) show the action is done <em>to yourself</em>: <span data-say=\"me levanto\">me levanto</span> (I get up), <span data-say=\"se levanta\">se levanta</span> (he/she gets up).</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> When a direct AND indirect pronoun combine, ‘le’/‘les’ change to <strong>se</strong>: <span data-say=\"Se lo doy a mi hermano.\">Se lo doy a mi hermano.</span> — <em>I give it to my brother.</em></p>", "question": "Which set of pronouns is used for reflexive verbs like ‘levantarse’?", "options": ["me, te, se, nos, os, se", "lo, la, los, las", "que, quien, lo que", "muy, bastante, demasiado"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Reflexive verbs take me/te/se/nos/os/se, matching the subject doing the action to itself."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:29859aa2', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Relative pronouns: que, quien, lo que", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"que\">que</span> (who/that/which) is the most common relative pronoun and works for <strong>both</strong> people and things: <span data-say=\"El chico que vive aquí es mi amigo.\">El chico que vive aquí es mi amigo.</span></p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"quien\">quien</span> / quienes <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> means ‘who’ but is normally used only for people, especially after a preposition: <span data-say=\"la persona con quien hablo\">la persona con quien hablo</span> (the person I talk to).</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"lo que\">lo que</span> <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> means ‘what / that which’ — it refers to an <strong>idea</strong>, not one specific noun: <span data-say=\"Hago lo que quiero.\">Hago lo que quiero.</span> (I do what I want.)</p>", "question": "Which relative pronoun means ‘what/that which’ and refers to an idea rather than one noun?", "options": ["lo que", "que", "quien", "quienes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘lo que’ sums up a whole idea (‘what I want’), while ‘que’ and ‘quien(es)’ replace a specific noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:f3b9edba', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Negatives: nada, nunca, nadie, ni…ni", "reading": "<p>Spanish uses a <strong>double negative</strong> — ‘no’ plus a negative word: <span data-say=\"no veo nada\">no veo nada</span> (I don’t see anything/I see nothing).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nada\">no … nada</span></td><td>nothing</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nunca\">no … nunca</span> / <span data-say=\"jamás\">jamás</span></td><td>never</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nadie\">no … nadie</span></td><td>nobody</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...ni...ni\">no … ni … ni</span></td><td>neither … nor</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Examples: <span data-say=\"no como nunca carne\">No como nunca carne.</span> (I never eat meat.) <span data-say=\"no hay nadie\">No hay nadie.</span> (There’s nobody.) <span data-say=\"no me gusta ni el fútbol ni el tenis\">No me gusta ni el fútbol ni el tenis.</span> (I like neither football nor tennis.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> You can drop ‘no’ if the negative word comes BEFORE the verb: <span data-say=\"nunca voy al gimnasio\">Nunca voy al gimnasio.</span> (I never go to the gym.)</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘I don’t see anything’ correctly in Spanish?", "options": ["No veo nada.", "No veo.", "Veo nada.", "No veo algo."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Spanish needs the double negative: no + veo + nada. Dropping ‘nada’, dropping ‘no’, or using ‘algo’ (something) are all wrong."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:ff3016a5', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Connectors and intensifiers", "reading": "<p>Basic connectors join ideas: <span data-say=\"y\">y</span> (and), <span data-say=\"pero\">pero</span> (but), <span data-say=\"porque\">porque</span> (because), <span data-say=\"también\">también</span> (also), <span data-say=\"además\">además</span> (furthermore).</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> For top marks add: <span data-say=\"sin embargo\">sin embargo</span> (however) and <span data-say=\"aunque\">aunque</span> (although) — <span data-say=\"aunque\">aunque</span> introduces a <strong>contrast</strong>, unlike ‘además’ which adds an idea.</p>\n            <p>Intensifiers strengthen or soften an adjective: <span data-say=\"muy\">muy</span> (very), <span data-say=\"bastante\">bastante</span> (quite), <span data-say=\"demasiado\">demasiado</span> (too much/many), <span data-say=\"un poco\">un poco</span> (a bit).</p>\n            <p>Example: <span data-say=\"Me gusta el deporte, pero prefiero la música. Además, toco la guitarra. Sin embargo, no tengo mucho tiempo.\">Me gusta el deporte, pero prefiero la música. Además, toco la guitarra. Sin embargo, no tengo mucho tiempo.</span></p>", "question": "Which connector means ‘although’ and introduces a contrast?", "options": ["aunque", "porque", "también", "además"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘aunque’ (although) signals a contrast; ‘porque’ gives a reason, and ‘también’/‘además’ add extra ideas rather than contrast them."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:8e87f87b', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Veo lo.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Lo veo.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘Veo lo’ wrong?", "options": ["the object pronoun must go BEFORE a conjugated verb (Lo veo)", "the pronoun ‘lo’ should be ‘la’ instead", "the verb ‘veo’ is spelt incorrectly", "object pronouns can never be used with a conjugated verb like ‘veo’, only with an infinitive such as ‘ver’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "With a conjugated verb the pronoun comes before it; it only attaches after an infinitive or gerund."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:12c80591', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Yo yo hablo español.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Hablo español.</p>", "question": "What’s wrong with doubling the pronoun in ‘Yo yo hablo’?", "options": ["the subject pronoun only needs using once, or can be dropped, since the verb ending shows ‘yo’", "‘yo’ must always be repeated twice in a row for extra emphasis in every single Spanish sentence you write", "‘hablo’ needs two subject pronouns to agree", "Spanish verbs cannot be used without two pronouns"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘Hablo’ already carries the meaning of ‘yo’; one pronoun (or none) is correct, never a double."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:080c5ceb', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> El libro quien compré es interesante.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> El libro que compré es interesante.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘el libro quien compré’ wrong?", "options": ["‘quien’ only refers to people, not things — things need ‘que’", "‘quien’ must always follow the word ‘lo’ before any noun or pronoun", "‘compré’ should be changed to ‘compro’", "‘libro’ needs a written accent on the final syllable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘quien/quienes’ refers to people; a thing like ‘el libro’ needs ‘que’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:10581af0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> No veo.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> No veo nada.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘No veo’ alone not correct for ‘I don’t see anything’?", "options": ["Spanish needs the double negative: no + veo + nada", "‘veo’ on its own already means ‘nothing’ without adding any other word", "‘no’ on its own already means ‘nothing’", "you should never use ‘no’ together with ‘ver’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Without ‘nada’, ‘No veo’ just means ‘I don’t see’ — it is missing what you don’t see."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:57128441', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Me gusta el deporte, aunque prefiero la música.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Me gusta el deporte, además prefiero la música.</p>", "question": "What’s the problem with ‘aunque’ here if you mean ‘as well as that’?", "options": ["‘aunque’ means ‘although’ and introduces a contrast, not an addition", "‘aunque’ is spelt incorrectly and should not appear anywhere in the sentence", "‘aunque’ can only be used to start a question", "‘aunque’ is one of the negative words like ‘nada’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘aunque’ signals a contrast (although); to ADD an idea you need ‘además’ or ‘también’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tips:0f74e702', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Paper 1 — Listening: pronouns and negatives in context", "reading": "Listen for whether the object pronoun is ‘lo/la’ (singular) or ‘los/las’ (plural), and for the negative word right after ‘no’ — ‘nada’, ‘nunca’ or ‘nadie’ completely change the meaning even though they sound similar.", "question": "You hear ‘no … nadie’. What does that tell you?", "options": ["nobody is involved", "nothing at all happened", "the action never happens", "everything is fine"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘no … nadie’ = nobody, not ‘nada’ (nothing) or ‘nunca’ (never)."}'::jsonb),
